root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>12237</fr:anchor><fr:addr>tfmt-000L</fr:addr><fr:route>tfmt-000L.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Generating images statically using LaTeX</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Because of the <fr:link
type="local"
href="tfmt-000J.xml"
addr="tfmt-000J"
title="Commutative diagrams in KaTeX">general</fr:link> <fr:link
type="local"
href="tfmt-000K.xml"
addr="tfmt-000K"
title="Commutative diagrams in MathJax">inadequacy</fr:link> <fr:link
type="local"
href="tfmt-000I.xml"
addr="tfmt-000I"
title="The quiver interactive diagramming tool">of</fr:link> the other available tools, most authors of hypertext mathematics with diagramming needs tend to rely on the static generation of images from LaTeX code using a local LaTeX toolchain. It is not difficult to instrument <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://www.pandoc.org/">pandoc</fr:link> with a <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://pandoc.org/lua-filters.html">Lua filter to render tikz code to SVG images</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>There are also a variety of other tools that do something similar, which tend to be employed in static site generation:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li><fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/antex">antex</fr:link> by <fr:link
type="local"
href="paolobrasolin.xml"
addr="paolobrasolin"
title="Paolo Brasolin">Paolo Brasolin</fr:link> is used by <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/krater">Krater</fr:link> as well as <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/jekyll-sheafy">jekyll-sheafy</fr:link>, both via <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/jekyll-antex">jekyll-antex</fr:link>.</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> by <fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jonathan Sterling</fr:link> is used by the present web site.</fr:li></fr:ul><fr:p>The basic architecture of such a tool is to scan for LaTeX blocks, and then identify them by a <fr:em>hash</fr:em> of their contents. This hash is used as a filename for <fr:code><![CDATA[.tex]]></fr:code> files, which are compiled to <fr:code><![CDATA[ .dvi]]></fr:code> and thence to <fr:code><![CDATA[.svg]]></fr:code> using the <fr:code><![CDATA[ dvisvgm]]></fr:code> tool; the resulting file is then embedded in HTML using an <fr:code><![CDATA[<img>]]></fr:code> tag. Alternatively,  is also possible to transclude the resulting <fr:code><![CDATA[<svg>]]></fr:code> element directly, but then <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/jekyll-antex/issues/26">one must be careful to rename all identifiers in the <fr:code><![CDATA[<svg>]]></fr:code> element uniquely</fr:link>, as it is possible for two different <fr:code><![CDATA[<svg>]]></fr:code> elements on a single page to interfere one each other.</fr:p><fr:p>Both <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/antex">antex</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> support passing a macro library to be used when rendering. Both <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://github.com/paolobrasolin/jekyll-sheafy">jekyll-sheafy</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> set their macro libraries on a page-local basis.</fr:p><fr:p>A serious downside of generating images from LaTeX code is the negative impact on accessibility tools. This seems only slightly mitigated by the transclusion of the <fr:code><![CDATA[<svg>]]></fr:code> element as opposed to using <fr:code><![CDATA[<img>]]></fr:code>. Ultimately accessibility for mathematical diagrams remains an unsolved problem, and it does not seem that the existing discussion on accessibility of hypertext mathematics has much to say about this problem.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>